Load libraries

# install.packages(c("gganimate", "gapminder", "ggridges", "devtools", "png", "gifski", "patchwork"))

library("patchwork") # for making figure panels
library("ggridges")  # for making joyplots 
library("gganimate") # for making animations
library("gapminder") # data available from Gapminder.org 
library("tidyverse") 

diamonds = diamonds

stacked bar chart

ggplot(data = diamonds,
       aes(x= cut,
           fill = color)
       )+
  geom_bar()

comparisons means & single data points

g = ggplot(
  diamonds,
  aes(x= color,
      y = price)
)

g + 
  stat_summary(fun.data = 'mean_cl_boot',
               color= 'pink',
               size= 1,
               geom = 'pointrange',
               shape= 21,
               fill = 'black'
               )

g +
  geom_point(color= 'orange',
             size= 2,
             alpha= 0.2,
             position = position_jitter(width = 0.1, height = 0)
             )

Violins for bimodal distributions

Violin plots are good when you have many data points and data is continuous.

ggplot(
  diamonds,
  aes(x= color, 
      y = price,
      fill= color)
)+
  geom_violin()

Density ridges

ggplot(
  diamonds,
  aes(x= price, 
      y = color,
      fill= color)
)+
  ggridges::geom_density_ridges()

Scatterplot

Scatterplot are good for lookiing at the relationship beyween 2 continuos variables

ggplot(
  diamonds,
  aes(x = carat,
      y= price,
      color= color)
)+
  geom_point()

Raster plots

Raster plots are useful for looking how a variable of interest varies as a function of 2 other variables.

Example: carat values differ from color and clarity.

ggplot(
  diamonds,
  aes(x= color,
      y= clarity,
      z = carat)
)+
  stat_summary2d(fun= 'mean', geom='tile')+
  scale_fill_gradient(low = 'purple' , high = 'yellow')
